events.name: Productivity Workshop: Test-Driven Development Part I
events.description:
TDD is a software development approach where a feature is built incrementally through the repetition of very short development cycles. In this approach, the process is started by turning a requirement into a specific test case, then code is written to pass the test, and then the cycle is repeated by adding a test for another feature requirement. Benefits of TDD include faster feedback, reduced scope creep and over-engineering, and modular and maintainable code.
In this workshop, you will learn TDD practices and how to implement this approach in your own projects.

What can I do with Ansible?  •  Provision infrastructure components on cloud e.g. compute, network, storage and other managed resources such as databases, caches etc.  • Install and configure system and application configurations  •  Software  Change management •  Deploy an application, do rolling updates etc.  •  Run ad-hoc commands on a group of servers in parallel 



Is this for me?  This workshop is for you if,  •  You are part of the ops team (systems/operations/network/infra engineers) and would like to learn how to manage systems at scale and automate common infrastructure tasks.  • If you are a part of development organization/ DevOps team and are involved in automating application deployments and orchestration.  • If you are a QA/Test engineer and are involved in building test infrastructure/setups frequently and use scripts or manual approach to doing that.   What topic will I  learn? •  Ansible quick overview  •  The language - YAML basics •  Playbooks - writing infrastructure as a code with Ansible •  Modules  -  The playbook plugins 



What will I  do during the workshop? •  Setup a cluster of Ansible nodes with a controller and 5 managed nodes •  Write a simple playbook to install an application and start service using core modules • Deploy application to the managed nodes  



What do I need to bring in?  •  BYOL - You bring in your own laptop. We will give you the software and the lab setup.   •  Internet Connectivity: We can not guarantee internet connectivity everywhere, so would be great if you come along with your own internet dongle, phone with wifi AP capabilities etc.   •  Lots of Enthusiasm: This is the most important pre-requisite :)

events.name: GTS Episode 3: Farewell Data Races; Safe Concurrency in Go vs Rust
events.description:
Concurrency by itself is easy until you start facing strange heisenbugs or hard to reproduce deadlocks. Safe concurrency is no piece of cake. Goroutines, channels, and select statement provided by Go make concurrent programming easy, but not necessarily safe. “Don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating. ” is idiomatic in Go, but it can hardly be enforced. In some cases using channels may be overkill, thus making "good old" synchronized sharing the most effective and convenient solution. However, sharing mutable data without proper synchronization leads to data races. This is the main cause of race conditions, aka Public Enemy #1. This talk will introduce two ways to avoid data races: detection in runtime with tools like the race detector provided by Go, and forbidding race conditions at compile time with the type system as Rust does. This talk will also explain why no data races does not mean no race conditions and will include a discussion on how to avoid race conditions in general. Speaker Cheng Wei Cheng Wei obtained his PhD degree from School of Computing, NUS on 2010, and then joined Garena and involved in various projects there. Since 2013, he worked as server team leader of BeeTalk, a social app having tens of millions of active users.

events.description: In Deep Learning (a specific technique in the ecosystem of AI) - lots of data is used to train the AI Algorithm - specifically deep neural networks. In this case, the data becomes part of the "code". Wrong input data - wrong models generated in the end. Hence it is critically important to track, trace and validate ALL data used to train and test the algorithm. Pachyderm is a data lake that offers complete version control for data and leverages the container ecosystem to provide reproducible data processing. As data scientists, we know the best ideas come through collaboration. We also know reproducibility matters. Pachyderm makes both a reality, and this talk shows how. We’ll talk about data containers and analysis pipelines, and how they combine to make Pachyderm a Git for Data Science and AI R&D. 6.30pm - 7.00pm : Networking 7.00pm - 7.40pm : Pachyderm - Git for Data Science by Najib NinabaNajib will share an overview of Pachyderm, infrastructure requirements and a quick demo of the installation and how-to. 7.50pm - 8.30pm : Using Pachyderm with RJeanne will share how a typical data scientist working with R and his/her datasets will be use Pachyderm to ensure reproducibility. Products he has managed and delivered includes Scalable Rocks, Platform Cluster Manager, Revolution Analytics's CloudR and RevoR integration into Cloudera Manager. events.name: How will robots affect our future?
events.description: It's in the headlines every day now: Future economy. Disruption. Loss of jobs. Machine learning. Learning machines. Robots. Uncertainty. Insecurity. Fear. Utopia. Freedom from work. Technological marvels. Abundance. The robots are coming, and we are helpless to stop them. Should we stop them, especially from taking our jobs? Or are they going to help us create an even better future? In an article appearing in the Straits Times on 6 March 2017, MIT research scientist Dr Andrew McAfee says:- Machines are going to put many people out of jobs- Jobs that require creative or social interaction skills are more likely to endure- Workers should acquire skills complementary to machines- Machines would create a world where labour costs drop to zero, people would be freed up to do things other than work, and there would be startling abundance- Education systems need to be overhauled- Countries need to develop an environment conducive to entrepreneurship, including investing in the right infrastructure and opening up to immigration- Governments need to support basic research while companies focus on applied research- Technological progress should not be held back- The big winners will be those who create and own the machines, while those on the wrong side of the divide will find it difficult to gain access to the bounty created These are just some of the common views that are circulating these days. Do you agree with them? What are your own view? Do you have ideas that can be integrated into a concrete plan of action? Do you think the use of artificial intelligence should be regulated by law? Do you think we need to modify our existing political and economic institutions to adapt to a future of robots? Come discuss and share!
